body:
So I was trying to use the `static_assertions` crate when I ran into a weird compiler error. I decided that, for testing purposes, it was worth it to just make it a runtime check rather than compile time. However, I ran into another issue. For example:

```rust
struct X {}
impl X{
    const CHECK: bool = false;
    fn new()->Self {
        assert!(Self::CHECK);
        Self {}
     }
}
fn main(){
    let _ = X::new();
    print!("done");
}
```
The assert won't produce an error at compile time, but it also won't produce an error at runtime (when `X::new()` is called). It gets completely compiled out, if you comment out the assert statement the exact same bytes are generated. 

I assume from a design perspective the expected behavior is essentially to replace the assert line with `panic!("...")`. That being said if it errored (or warned) at compile time I think that would also be reasonable. 

### Meta
This applies to both the stable and nightly versions of `rustc`.
